section.t:
The rationale of this section is to list issues that need consideration when designing a transport protocol that is meant to be used by most Internet users: 
        Limited rate;
        Varying capacity (L2 mechanisms where path varies with time);
        (significant) Asymmetry in rate;
        Higher RTT (GEO - and effect of BoD);
        Varying RTT (RACK instead of FR, but could work strangely with L2 mechanisms on the last hop - 1/8 RTT is an ad hoc choice that could cause issues. Satellite constellations with low earth orbit and large variations.);
        Multiple very different paths (e.g. satellite and 5g);
        Limited PMTU - effects of multiple encapsulations;
        Manageability;
        Explicit proxies (shared certificates, etc);

The transport is particularly impacted: 
	Effect of delay on setup exchanges;
	Inadequate slow-start;
        Appreciate loss (impact of Transmission Loss/Recovery - unrecovered loss) in time-based reliability schemes.

Potential mechanisms (a small starter list): 
	Dynamic Ack Ratio (faster growth, high asymmetry);
	Larger initial window (with safety for larger RTT): IW limited by a window per second (as a function of a minimal pacing);
	Harmonization of the transport reliability.
